{"title_page": "Clayton County commuter rail", "text_new": "{{Clayton County commuter rail}}\n'''Clayton County commuter rail''' is a planned [[commuter rail]] line traversing [[Clayton County, Georgia]] and connecting with the [[Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority|MARTA]] [[rapid transit]] system at [[East Point station]].\n\nAfter Clayton County joined the MARTA system in 2014, MARTA began studying alternatives for high-capacity transit through the county. Commuter rail was selected as the locally preferred alternative in 2018.\n\nThe line may break ground in 2023, with revenue service between East Point and [[Jonesboro, Georgia|Jonesboro]] beginning in 2027.<ref name=MARTAapproves />\n\n==History==\n===Planning by GDOT===\n{{Main|Georgia Rail Passenger Program}}\nPotential routes for commuter rail service in metropolitan Atlanta were studied by the [[Georgia Department of Transportation]] (GDOT) beginning in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/rail/Reports/Rpt/commuterrail.shtml |title=GDOT - Commuter Rail |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021218062539/http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/rail/Reports/Rpt/commuterrail.shtml |archive-date=December 18, 2002 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Eventually, plans for a system of seven lines radiating out from [[Five Points, Atlanta]] were developed and dubbed the [[Georgia Rail Passenger Program]]. The program included one line running through Clayton County and terminating in [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dot.ga.gov/InvestSmart/Rail/Documents/GRPPFactSheet2006.pdf |title=Georgia Rail Passenger Program 2006 Fact Sheet |access-date=December 18, 2019 | df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nBy 2004, GDOT's effort had concentrated on two lines terminating in [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] (a shortened Macon line) and [[Athens, Georgia|Athens]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/ |title=Office of Intermodal Program--Rail Index |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040906055758/http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/ |archive-date=September 6, 2004|url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> At the time, the planned Lovejoy line was anticipated to open in 2006 and $106 million in federal funding was earmarked for the project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.state.ga.us:80/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/Documents/PDF/Lovejoy%20Commuter%20Rail%20fact%20sheet.pdf |title=Lovejoy Commuter Rail fact sheet |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040302014011/http://www.dot.state.ga.us:80/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/Documents/PDF/Lovejoy%20Commuter%20Rail%20fact%20sheet.pdf |archive-date=September 6, 2004 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Clayton County Board of Commissioners was supportive of the line, asking the state government to advance the plan.<ref>{{cite news |last1= Corriher |first1= Billy |url=https://www.news-daily.com/news/county-requests-atlanta-lovejoy-rail-line/article_7cf4fb09-0fe6-52b9-a3f5-911cb62ade25.html |title=County requests Atlanta-Lovejoy rail line |date=December 16, 2003 |access-date=December 18, 2019 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, after years of inaction from the state on the project, then-governor [[Sonny Perdue]] announced his support for the Lovejoy line. This was speculated to be partially due to the project being in danger of losing its federal funding because of a lack of progress.<ref>{{cite news |last1= Saporta |first1= Maria |url=http://www.ajc.com/blogs/content/shared-blogs/ajc/businessinsider/entries/2008/06/15/at_last_perdue_gets_aboard_on.html |title=At last, Gov. Perdue on board for commuter rail |date=June 15, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522085502/http://www.ajc.com/blogs/content/shared-blogs/ajc/businessinsider/entries/2008/06/15/at_last_perdue_gets_aboard_on.html |archive-date=May 11, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Due to further inaction, the federal government withdrew the funds it had previously appropriated for the project in July 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Simmons |first1=Andria |url=https://www.governing.com/news/headlines/mct-commuter-rail-atlanta.html |title=Feds Take Back Millions in Unused Money for Atlanta Commuter Rail |date=July 11, 2014 |access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Planning by MARTA===\nOn July 5, 2014, the Clayton County Board of Commissioners approved a contract with [[Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority|MARTA]] to extend service to the county by a margin of 3-1, financed by a 1% sales tax. Fulton and DeKalb county leaders approved the expansion and on November 4, 2014, Clayton County residents approved the 1% sales tax to join MARTA. The contract reserves half of the collected tax revenue for the development of rail transit in the county, with the other half funding local bus service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://clatl.com/freshloaf/archives/2014/07/05/clayton-approves-marta-contract-for-november-ballot |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714154106/http://clatl.com/freshloaf/archives/2014/07/05/clayton-approves-marta-contract-for-november-ballot| archive-date=July 14, 2014 |title=Clayton approves MARTA contract for November ballot |publisher=Creative Loafing Atlanta |author=John Ruch |date=2014-07-05}}</ref>\n\nCommuter rail was selected in 2018 as the locally preferred alternative of transit mode along the corridor,<ref name=saportaMARTAchoice >{{cite news |last1=Saporta |first1=Maria |title=Commuter rail is MARTA\u2019s choice for Clayton County |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2018/07/13/commuter-rail-is-marta-s-choice-for-clayton-county.html |accessdate=13 July 2018 |agency=Atlanta Business Journal |date=13 July 2018}}</ref> which was later approved by the MARTA Board of Directors.<ref name=MARTAapproves>{{cite news |last1=Wickert |first1=David |title=MARTA approves plans for Clayton County commuter train |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/marta-approves-plans-for-clayton-county-commuter-train/TGCcz6JGlUOxvzLzQTtUnJ/ |accessdate=8 December 2018 |agency=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 11, 2020, all four MARTA jurisdictions passed the 15th amendment to the Rapid Transit Contract and Assistance Agreement (RTCAA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itsmarta.com/jurisdictions-pass-15th-amendment.aspx|title=MARTA|website=www.itsmarta.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. The amendment enables MARTA to proceed with expansion projects in Clayton County. An attached exhibit lists several high-capacity transit projects, including commuter rail transit (CRT) and bus rapid transit (BRT). MARTA has committed to continued planning and design on the Clayton County Commuter Rail project, which will stretch 22 miles from East Point Station to Lovejoy, with the first phase (about 11 miles) from East Point to South Lake Mall up and running by 2030.\n\n==Route[[Javascript:void(0);]]==\nThe line follows the existing [[Norfolk Southern]] [[right of way]] from [[East Point station]] to [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] in southern Clayton County, a distance of {{convert|22|mi}}.<ref name=MARTAapproves /> MARTA is negotiating with Norfolk Southern to install tracks in their right of way, adjacent to the freight line.<ref name=saportaMARTAchoice />\n\nOne version of the proposal calls for stations at [[Hapeville, Georgia|Hapeville]], [[Mountain View, Georgia|Mountain View]], [[Forest Park, Georgia|Forest Park]], [[Fort Gillem]], [[Clayton State University]], [[Morrow, Georgia|Morrow]] and [[Jonesboro, Georgia|Jonesboro]]. A station in  [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] is also proposed, which would open as a later phase.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.itsmarta.com/uploadedFiles/News_And_Events/Clayton-County-MARTA-Map.pdf |title=MARTA Proposed Clayton County Service in 2025 |access-date=November 12, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052952/http://www.itsmarta.com/uploadedFiles/News_And_Events/Clayton-County-MARTA-Map.pdf |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> \n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.itsmarta.com/clayton-county-overview.aspx MARTA overiew]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MARTA Nav}}\n[[Category:Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority]]\n[[Category:Proposed railway lines in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Clayton County commuter rail}}\n'''Clayton County commuter rail''' is a planned [[commuter rail]] line traversing [[Clayton County, Georgia]] and connecting with the [[Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority|MARTA]] [[rapid transit]] system at [[East Point station]].\n\nAfter Clayton County joined the MARTA system in 2014, MARTA began studying alternatives for high-capacity transit through the county. Commuter rail was selected as the locally preferred alternative in 2018.\n\nThe line may break ground in 2023, with revenue service between East Point and [[Jonesboro, Georgia|Jonesboro]] beginning in 2027.<ref name=MARTAapproves />\n\n==History==\n===Planning by GDOT===\n{{Main|Georgia Rail Passenger Program}}\nPotential routes for commuter rail service in metropolitan Atlanta were studied by the [[Georgia Department of Transportation]] (GDOT) beginning in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/rail/Reports/Rpt/commuterrail.shtml |title=GDOT - Commuter Rail |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021218062539/http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/rail/Reports/Rpt/commuterrail.shtml |archive-date=December 18, 2002 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Eventually, plans for a system of seven lines radiating out from [[Five Points, Atlanta]] were developed and dubbed the [[Georgia Rail Passenger Program]]. The program included one line running through Clayton County and terminating in [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dot.ga.gov/InvestSmart/Rail/Documents/GRPPFactSheet2006.pdf |title=Georgia Rail Passenger Program 2006 Fact Sheet |access-date=December 18, 2019 | df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nBy 2004, GDOT's effort had concentrated on two lines terminating in [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] (a shortened Macon line) and [[Athens, Georgia|Athens]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/ |title=Office of Intermodal Program--Rail Index |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040906055758/http://www.dot.state.ga.us/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/ |archive-date=September 6, 2004|url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> At the time, the planned Lovejoy line was anticipated to open in 2006 and $106 million in federal funding was earmarked for the project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.state.ga.us:80/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/Documents/PDF/Lovejoy%20Commuter%20Rail%20fact%20sheet.pdf |title=Lovejoy Commuter Rail fact sheet |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040302014011/http://www.dot.state.ga.us:80/dot/plan-prog/intermodal/Rail/Documents/PDF/Lovejoy%20Commuter%20Rail%20fact%20sheet.pdf |archive-date=September 6, 2004 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Clayton County Board of Commissioners was supportive of the line, asking the state government to advance the plan.<ref>{{cite news |last1= Corriher |first1= Billy |url=https://www.news-daily.com/news/county-requests-atlanta-lovejoy-rail-line/article_7cf4fb09-0fe6-52b9-a3f5-911cb62ade25.html |title=County requests Atlanta-Lovejoy rail line |date=December 16, 2003 |access-date=December 18, 2019 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, after years of inaction from the state on the project, then-governor [[Sonny Perdue]] announced his support for the Lovejoy line. This was speculated to be partially due to the project being in danger of losing its federal funding because of a lack of progress.<ref>{{cite news |last1= Saporta |first1= Maria |url=http://www.ajc.com/blogs/content/shared-blogs/ajc/businessinsider/entries/2008/06/15/at_last_perdue_gets_aboard_on.html |title=At last, Gov. Perdue on board for commuter rail |date=June 15, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522085502/http://www.ajc.com/blogs/content/shared-blogs/ajc/businessinsider/entries/2008/06/15/at_last_perdue_gets_aboard_on.html |archive-date=May 11, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Due to further inaction, the federal government withdrew the funds it had previously appropriated for the project in July 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Simmons |first1=Andria |url=https://www.governing.com/news/headlines/mct-commuter-rail-atlanta.html |title=Feds Take Back Millions in Unused Money for Atlanta Commuter Rail |date=July 11, 2014 |access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Planning by MARTA===\nOn July 5, 2014, the Clayton County Board of Commissioners approved a contract with [[Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority|MARTA]] to extend service to the county by a margin of 3-1, financed by a 1% sales tax. Fulton and DeKalb county leaders approved the expansion and on November 4, 2014, Clayton County residents approved the 1% sales tax to join MARTA. The contract reserves half of the collected tax revenue for the development of rail transit in the county, with the other half funding local bus service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://clatl.com/freshloaf/archives/2014/07/05/clayton-approves-marta-contract-for-november-ballot |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714154106/http://clatl.com/freshloaf/archives/2014/07/05/clayton-approves-marta-contract-for-november-ballot| archive-date=July 14, 2014 |title=Clayton approves MARTA contract for November ballot |publisher=Creative Loafing Atlanta |author=John Ruch |date=2014-07-05}}</ref>\n\nCommuter rail was selected in 2018 as the locally preferred alternative of transit mode along the corridor,<ref name=saportaMARTAchoice >{{cite news |last1=Saporta |first1=Maria |title=Commuter rail is MARTA\u2019s choice for Clayton County |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2018/07/13/commuter-rail-is-marta-s-choice-for-clayton-county.html |accessdate=13 July 2018 |agency=Atlanta Business Journal |date=13 July 2018}}</ref> which was later approved by the MARTA Board of Directors.<ref name=MARTAapproves>{{cite news |last1=Wickert |first1=David |title=MARTA approves plans for Clayton County commuter train |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/marta-approves-plans-for-clayton-county-commuter-train/TGCcz6JGlUOxvzLzQTtUnJ/ |accessdate=8 December 2018 |agency=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Route==\nThe line follows the existing [[Norfolk Southern]] [[right of way]] from [[East Point station]] to [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] in southern Clayton County, a distance of {{convert|22|mi}}.<ref name=MARTAapproves /> MARTA is negotiating with Norfolk Southern to install tracks in their right of way, adjacent to the freight line.<ref name=saportaMARTAchoice />\n\nOne version of the proposal calls for stations at [[Hapeville, Georgia|Hapeville]], [[Mountain View, Georgia|Mountain View]], [[Forest Park, Georgia|Forest Park]], [[Fort Gillem]], [[Clayton State University]], [[Morrow, Georgia|Morrow]] and [[Jonesboro, Georgia|Jonesboro]]. A station in  [[Lovejoy, Georgia|Lovejoy]] is also proposed, which would open as a later phase.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.itsmarta.com/uploadedFiles/News_And_Events/Clayton-County-MARTA-Map.pdf |title=MARTA Proposed Clayton County Service in 2025 |access-date=November 12, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052952/http://www.itsmarta.com/uploadedFiles/News_And_Events/Clayton-County-MARTA-Map.pdf |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> \n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.itsmarta.com/clayton-county-overview.aspx MARTA overiew]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MARTA Nav}}\n[[Category:Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority]]\n[[Category:Proposed railway lines in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rynmrrs", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Updated Planning by MARTA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clayton_County_commuter_rail"}
{"title_page": "A.J.K. Mass Communication Research Centre", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name           = A.J.K. Mass Communication Research Centre\n| native_name    = \n| native_name_lang = \n| other_name     = \n| former_name    = \n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| image_alt      = \n| caption        = \n| latin_name     = \n| motto          = \n| motto_lang     = \n| mottoeng       = \n| established    = {{Start date|1982}}\n| closed         = <!-- {{End date|YYYY}} -->\n| type           = Research Centre\n| affiliation    = [[Jamia Millia Islamia]]\n| academic_affiliation    = [[CILECT]]\n| endowment      = \n| budget         = \n| officer_in_charge = \n| chairman       = \n| chancellor     = \n| president      = \n| vice-president = \n| superintendent = \n| provost        = \n| vice_chancellor= \n| rector         = \n| principal      = \n| dean           = \n| director       = \n| head_label     = \n| head           = \n| academic_staff = \n| administrative_staff = \n| students       = \n| undergrad      = \n| postgrad       = \n| doctoral       = \n| other          = \n| city           = [[New Delhi]]\n| state          = \n| province       = \n| country        = [[India]]\n| coor           = \n| campus         = \n| former_names   = \n| language       = \n| free_label     = \n| free           = \n| colors         = \n| colours        = \n| athletics      = \n| sports         = \n| nickname       = \n| mascot         = \n| affiliations   = \n| website        = {{URL|http://jmi.ac.in/aboutjamia/centres/mcrc/introduction}}\n| logo           = \n| footnotes      = \n}}\n\n'''A.J.K. Mass Communication Research Centre''' ('''AJK MCRC''') is a [[mass communication]] [[research center]] located in [[New Delhi]], [[India]] and a [[constituent college|constituent institute]] of [[Jamia Millia Islamia]].\n\n==Academics==\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2017}}\nThe center offers courses including M.A. courses in Mass Communication, Convergent Journalism, Development Communication, Graphics and Animation as well as post graduate diplomas in, Still Photography, Acting and Broadcast Technology. The Center has the course of Convergent Journalism, an integrated master's degree program in print, broadcast, online and photo journalism.\n\n==Facilities==\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2017}}\n\n===Production facilities===\nThe AJK MCRC has analogue and digital systems for programme production. There are three television studios for multi-camera productions and DV and HDV cameras (PD-150, PD-170, HVR Z-1, DSR 570 and Panasonic DVX 100) with accessories for single camera shoots. Other production equipment includes final cut pro non-linear editing machines of the G5 series, with dual processors for film & video, Avid Adrenaline Media Composers, Arriflex 16 SR III film cameras, Steinbeck film editing machines, digital audio work stations, sound studio, multimedia lab with software for print journalism, and still photography units. Recent additions to the production equipment include the Magnum Dolly system and the PICCOLO crane.\n\n[[BBC]] programmes Hard Talk India and Face To Face which were presented by [[Karan Thapar]] were shot inside the television studio at AJK MCRC. Programmes were produced with the assistance of AJK MCRC's staff and featured some of the biggest names in Indian public life.\n\n===Media library===\nThe media library has books, journals, films, video cassettes, audio cassettes, stock shots, and press clippings for the use of students. Students can use the Zakir Hussian Library of the university.\n\n===Community radio===\nThe AJK MCRC as a part of its social commitment and responsibility towards the community within which it is situated, runs a community radio station on 90.4 FM. Addressing itself to the residents of the Jamia area, RADIO JAMIA broadcasts educational, enrichment and a wide range of rich socio-cultural programmes. These programmes can be heard around a radius of 10 kilometres on the Jamia campus. Currently, the radio programmes are produced by the students and the faculty of the AJK MCRC in collaboration with different groups and organisation in Delhi. \n\nAs per ''[[The Hindu]]'', \"Radio Jamia, which started in 2005, broadcasts shows from 2-5 p.m. and replays the previous day\u2019s broadcast from 10 a.m. to 1 p.m. The programme broadcast include an hour-long ghazal segment and a 20-minute dedicated show for regional songs covering diverse linguistic communities residing in its service area, apart from shows on education, health, sports and social issues.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/community-radio-makes-waves/article6255775.ece|title=Community radio makes waves|first=Akshita|last=Nagpal|date=28 July 2014|publisher=|via=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\n===Media Resource Center===\nThe Media Resource Centre at the AJK MCRC is an archive and theory centre devoted to documentary, film and contemporary media [https://www.jmientrance.com practices]. It has been set up through a grant from Sir Ratan Tata Trust.\n\n==Student achievements==\n\nUnder the guidance of Professor [[Farhat Basir Khan]], MCRC students Neal Kartik and Pranab Kumar Aich won the prestigious 'Student Focus Competition' at Sony World Photography Awards 2009, [[Cannes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/indian-students-win-global-photo-awards-392211|title=Indian students win global photo awards|publisher=}}</ref> Jamia's team achieved the feat by defeating 60 of the world's best universities across continents and bagged a cash prize of 50,000 Euros.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2009/20090509/delhi.htm#10|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Delhi and neighbourhood|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Ranking==\nAJK MCRC was ranked #1 in ''[[Outlook India]]''{{'}}s \"Top Mass Comm Colleges In 2017\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Top Mass Comm Colleges In 2017|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/top-mass-comm-colleges-in-2017/298920|accessdate=5 September 2017|work=[[Outlook India]]|date=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt has been consistently rated as amongst the top mass-communication colleges in [[Asia]].\n\n<br />\n\n==Affiliations==\n*[[CILECT]]{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n* CILECT Asia-Pacific Association (CAPA){{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{alumni|date=September 2017}}\n* [[Roshan Abbas]], TV Anchor & RJ\n* [[Harsh Chhaya]], Film Actor\n* [[Barkha Dutt]], Consulting Editor, [[NDTV]]; [[Padma Shri]] recipient.\n* [[Meenu Gaur ]], Screenwriter & Director<ref>{{cite web|title=Zinda Bhaag: a Pakistani film which feels Indian|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/zinda-bhaag-a-pakistani-film-which-feels-indian/story-QX7RmjehodcrRoRblrC6XN.html/|website=Hindustan Times|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Ritu Kapur]], Media entrepreneur<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reutersinstitute.politics.ox.ac.uk/people/ritu-kapur|title=Ritu Kapur {{!}} Reuters Institute for the Study of Journalism|website=reutersinstitute.politics.ox.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref>\n* [[Habib Faisal]], Screenwriter & Director\n* [[Shazia Ilmi]], News Anchor & Politician\n* [[Nishtha Jain]], Noted Documentary Film-maker\n*[[Sharat Katariya]], Film Director\n* [[Kabir Khan (director)|Kabir Khan]], Celebrated Film Director<ref>{{cite news|title=Overthere|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/1080313/jsp/careergraph/story_9011094.jsp|accessdate=8 March 2018|work=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n*[[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]], Noted Film Actor; [[Padma Shri]] and [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]] recipient (Did not Graduate)\n* [[Hardik Mehta]], Filmmaker\n* [[Kiran Rao]], [[Bollywood]]; Film director and Producer<ref>http://archive.tehelka.com/story_main48.asp?filename=hub220111DEAR_MR.asp</ref>\n* [[Alankrita Shrivastava]